Tacitus describes inexactly the marriage by purchase‚ prevalent in his time in Germany. This usage, which in primitive society succeeded marriage by capture, was in vogue in Homeric Greece and existed among the Thracians in the time of Xenophon, to whom Seuthes says, Anabasis 7. 2. 38, ‘ If you have a daughter, I will buy her according to the Thracian eustom! The dos constituted the price paid for the transfer of the woman from the potestas of her father to that of her husband; it was not paid to her, as Tacitus sayS‚ but to her parents. The inaccuracy of Tacitus is due to his desire to make the contrast between Roman and German practice as pointed as possible. A later step involved giving the portion or a part of it to the bride.
